item.title: U.S. Sanctions Chinese Firms Active in Contested South China Sea
item.description: The U.S. unveiled visa and export restrictions against Chinese state-owned companies and their executives involved in advancing Beijing’s territorial claims in the contested South China Sea.

item.title: Iran Grants U.N. Watchdog Access to Suspected Nuclear Sites
item.description: Tehran agreed to allow United Nations inspectors access to two sites where it is suspected of carrying out illicit nuclear-weapons work in the past, bowing to months of pressure in a bid to salvage backing for the 2015 nuclear deal.

item.title: Israel Attacks Hezbollah Posts on Lebanese Border in Retaliatory Fire
item.description: Israel’s military said it struck Hezbollah observation posts along the Lebanese frontier in response to overnight cross-border fire, adding to a recent flare-up of tensions between the two sides.

item.title: U.S. Warns of Global Bank Heist Campaign by North Korean Hackers
item.description: Hackers tied to the North Korean government are trying to rob banks across the globe by draining ATMs and initiating fraudulent transfers, an effort by the cash-strapped regime to fund its nuclear weapons program, government agencies said Wednesday.

item.title: Greece Asserts a Maritime Claim Amid Dispute With Turkey
item.description: Greece, facing an escalating maritime dispute with Turkey, sought to show its determination by expanding its territorial waters in another direction: in the Ionian Sea, facing Italy.

item.title: Saudi Arabia Barrels Ahead With Big Projects to Boost Economy
item.description: The kingdom is moving forward with multibillion-dollar plans to build cities despite the Covid-19 pandemic and depressed oil prices, betting that projects closely associated with the crown prince will kick-start its economic recovery.
